ChatterBot now supports in-memory databases. If you configure the SQL storage adapter in read-only mode it will achieve the effect desired here because it won't create a database and no statements will be added to it.

```python
bot = ChatBot("Terminal",
    storage_adapter={
        'import_path': 'chatterbot.storage.SQLStorageAdapter',
        'read_only': True
    }
)
```

Thanks for the help.  Flask-Restful was hijacking the errors.  I figured out a good work around.  I overrode the flask-restful error_router method to defer to the original handler for Flask-JWT errors.

**I replaced this line in my code:**
```python
api = Api(app)
```
**With the following**
```python
class ErrorFriendlyApi(Api):
    def error_router(self, original_handler, e):
        if type(e) is JWTError:
            return original_handler(e)
        else:
            return super(ErrorFriendlyApi, self).error_router(original_handler, e)

api = ErrorFriendlyApi(app)#, errors=errors)
```

