@fxsjy Thanks for the information you've provided. The fundamental issue you're running into seems to be that `_produce` holds `_update_lock`, which becomes a problem when the producer's internal queue is full most of the time (that is, when `max_queued_messages` is low compared to the message production rate). When `_update` is [called in `_send request`](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/647f174d53527c3d16249290c6f328a74639cc23/pykafka/producer.py#L449), it immediately [waits](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/647f174d53527c3d16249290c6f328a74639cc23/pykafka/producer.py#L228) to acquire `_update_lock`. Meanwhile, the main thread has spent most of its time [holding `_update_lock`](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/647f174d53527c3d16249290c6f328a74639cc23/pykafka/producer.py#L371) and [waiting for `slot_available`](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/647f174d53527c3d16249290c6f328a74639cc23/pykafka/producer.py#L666), since the queue is usually full. The main thread is holding `_update_lock` and waiting on `slot_available`, and the worker thread is waiting on `_update_lock` and holding `slot_available` - ie a deadlock.

The worker thread's call to `_update` obviously needs to hold `update_lock`, so I think the most appealing way to fix this issue is to stop the main thread from holding the lock during `enqueue` calls, which you've taken a stab at here. The way you've gone about it renders the lock in `_produce` mostly useless, so I'm thinking it might make sense to remove the `with self._update_lock:` line entirely. I checked out my [notes](https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/pull/595) from when this locking behavior was added and ran some local tests with the locking removed. I'm actually not able to replicate the issue mentioned in #595 when I remove the lock in `_produce`, which makes me wish I'd taken better notes!

Please revise this pull request to simply remove `with self._update_lock:` from `_produce` - all of the other changes in the diff seem unnecessary to me (please correct me if I'm overlooking something basic). If you agree that this change fixes the issue you're seeing, we may be able to merge it in and get it tested as a dev release. Thanks again for your contributions!

